p.
  Since I'd been doing independent research into geosocial networking security and Facebook data analysis myself, it made sense to present this research and its results alongside other research which I believed may be of a similar quality and depth (research by PhD students). This was obviously a brave move since I'm still only a second year undergraduate student (as it happens I was the only undergraduate student who presented), but it was worth it.

p.
  My research was divided into 2 distinct areas both in the field of social networking analysis. The first area (chronologically) looked at the security of geosocial networking, seeking in particular to use a flaw in the Grindr mobile application to identify exactly where its users lived from anywhere in the world. The second area looked at parsing, processing and analysing a personal archive from Facebook to provide a testing platform on which, for example, the most negative people with whom the user had chatted could be identified. The current focus of this research is now on generating a Social Graph from the processed chat logs which is far more accurate than one derived from public data such as friend connections or &lsquo;likes&rsquo;.

