p
  |Of the two areas, I was comfortable presenting the Facebook data analysis research because I had already gained confidence in its credibility and level of interest from giving a talk on it to The Computing Society earlier in the year, before I was elected President. The President at a previous time had also congratulated me on my Grindr investigations informally at a free-pizza-bearing-bear-all-half-price-cocktails night out at 
  a(href="http://daltonrooms.co.uk/") Dalton Rooms
  | in town (in those days I used to go out more than once a month). This gave me the confidence that I could present both as part of cumulative research in the same social networking analysis field.

p.
  I decided against giving a demonstration because my research is not of the &lsquo;dynamic, live and exciting&rsquo; nature. It takes seconds of computation to parse and process the personal archive from Facebook, for example. As another example, I have never found demonstrations of statistics projects interesting (I think they hold greater merit when presented statically as well). Therefore, I presented a poster which summarised my methodologies, results and analyses. Of course, since I am also into clean, beautiful and functional design, a goal of the poster was to present the research attractively &mdash; this isn't common in research, I'm sad to reveal.

